	<main>
		<img width="1920" height="922" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="moss covered unfinished canoe" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe.jpg 1920w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-haida-canoe-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">An unfinished canoe abandoned in a remote forest in southeast Alaska roughly 140 years ago may hold secrets about traditional Haida boatmaking techniques. Photo by Luke Holton</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Canoe in the Forest</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">An unfinished boat hidden on a remote island in Alaska illuminates a missing chapter in the history of traditional Haida and Tlingit canoe building</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/josh-hunt/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Joshua Hunt</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						December 19, 2024 | 3,500 words, about 17 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
